1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:12,520
 Ok, so the most dramatic thing during the presentation is to share the PowerPoint.

2
00:00:12,520 --> 00:00:18,100
 If I see this correctly, I was successful in it.

3
00:00:18,100 --> 00:00:28,300
 So I'm very grateful to my friend Stjepan Štivić and also to all organizers for this invitation.

4
00:00:29,200 --> 00:00:39,060
 I indeed think this kind of confidence is very important and I'm very sorry that I can't be with you today in person,

5
00:00:39,060 --> 00:00:45,440
 but I will try to make this better on some other occasion.

6
00:00:45,440 --> 00:00:58,400
 So the notion that the relationships between the church and secular authorities is different

7
00:00:58,400 --> 00:01:03,900
 in Western and Eastern Christianity is much widespread.

8
00:01:03,900 --> 00:01:12,100
 And it was probably only corroborated by a relatively fresh experience

9
00:01:12,100 --> 00:01:23,180
 when many Orthodox and Catholic believers in Central and Eastern Europe lived under communism quite recently.

10
00:01:24,260 --> 00:01:34,020
 And there it was a notion that the Catholic Church, despite of all difficulties,

11
00:01:34,020 --> 00:01:41,960
 showed greater resilience in her relationship to secular authorities.

12
00:01:41,960 --> 00:01:57,880
 But the point of my paper will be that this difference was not caused by ideal foundations,

13
00:01:57,880 --> 00:02:14,980
 because both Eastern and Western Christianity shared, in fact, main foundations of formation of these relationships between throne and altar.

14
00:02:16,880 --> 00:02:27,080
 The first experience of Christians in the very beginnings of Christianity was twofold.

15
00:02:27,080 --> 00:02:43,360
 On one hand, for the first 300 years, Christians used to live in an environment where both secular authorities

16
00:02:43,360 --> 00:02:57,540
 and the majority pagan environment mainly chose to simply ignore them as if Christian communities didn't exist.

17
00:03:00,820 --> 00:03:09,540
 That's very important, because it formed ever since a part of Christian DNA,

18
00:03:09,540 --> 00:03:19,420
 because Christians instinctively knew that there would be situations

19
00:03:19,420 --> 00:03:26,220
 where they absolutely couldn't rely on secular authorities.

20
00:03:26,220 --> 00:03:36,680
 Of course, this basic situation from the antiquity was later changed in both West and the East,

21
00:03:36,680 --> 00:03:45,020
 but nevertheless, it still remained an important early experience.

22
00:03:45,020 --> 00:03:53,180
 On the other hand, Christians were faced from the very beginning with a great problem

23
00:03:53,180 --> 00:04:01,820
 in their relationships to secular power, to secular or political authorities.

24
00:04:01,820 --> 00:04:06,940
 If they took their Christianity seriously,

25
00:04:06,940 --> 00:04:14,540
 They couldn't take part in the worship of the emperor,

26
00:04:14,540 --> 00:04:25,980
 which became the link between all subjects of the Roman Empire very early in the history of Christianity.

27
00:04:25,980 --> 00:04:32,860
 So, they tried to compensate for this great handicap

28
00:04:32,860 --> 00:04:46,780
 by affirming their steadfast loyalty to secular power and to the person of emperor himself.

29
00:04:46,780 --> 00:04:57,260
 And this is already visible in early scriptural foundations in the early New Testament texts,

30
00:04:57,260 --> 00:05:08,220
 particularly in the famous passage from the letter of the Apostle St. Paul to the Romans in 13th chapter,

31
00:05:08,220 --> 00:05:16,940
 where there are almost no limitations put on secular authority,

32
00:05:16,940 --> 00:05:23,180
 because it is divine in origin in St. Paul's view.

33
00:05:23,180 --> 00:05:39,740
 And I even have the impression that this secular authority didn't have any real obligations towards its subjects.

34
00:05:40,780 --> 00:05:47,980
 Why St. Paul put the things so radically and drastically,

35
00:05:47,980 --> 00:05:52,460
 particularly in view of the later development?

36
00:05:52,460 --> 00:06:00,940
 I think he did so because he expected the second coming of Christ very soon,

37
00:06:01,500 --> 00:06:11,020
 so he assumed that this question of the relationship between church and state wouldn't be of much importance.

38
00:06:11,020 --> 00:06:15,260
 His view was later echoed

39
00:06:15,260 --> 00:06:26,140
 also by some other New Testament texts, particularly by the first epistle of St. Peter in the second chapter,

40
00:06:27,020 --> 00:06:32,700
 where the main tone is the same as in the Romans.

41
00:06:32,700 --> 00:06:39,820
 Of course, there is also another current present in the New Testament,

42
00:06:39,820 --> 00:06:46,940
 particularly in the last book of the New Testament, in the Revelation of St. John,

43
00:06:46,940 --> 00:06:52,620
 where Rome is clearly identified as Babylon

44
00:06:53,820 --> 00:07:00,540
 and seen in a much degradating view.

45
00:07:00,540 --> 00:07:06,940
 But this current was clearly a minority view among Christians in antiquity and

46
00:07:06,940 --> 00:07:11,580
 also during the later periods, although this current existed.

47
00:07:12,380 --> 00:07:23,260
 It must also be said that another very important passage for the formation of relationship between church and state,

48
00:07:23,260 --> 00:07:30,140
 the scene of Caesar's coin in Synoptic Gospels,

49
00:07:30,140 --> 00:07:35,180
 is much more ambiguous than the passage by St. Paul.

50
00:07:36,220 --> 00:07:42,380
 Although there was a tendency among Christian writers to interpret

51
00:07:42,380 --> 00:07:49,020
 this passage also in a way more favorable to the emperor.

52
00:07:49,020 --> 00:07:53,740
 Although, in my view, it is clear from the words of Jesus

53
00:07:54,460 --> 00:08:04,140
 that the real emphasis is on the notion that there are spheres where the emperor had no end.

54
00:08:04,140 --> 00:08:13,180
 These scriptural foundations and this basic experience of the relation to void secular power

55
00:08:13,180 --> 00:08:20,060
 is clearly shared by Western and Eastern Christianity.

56
00:08:20,060 --> 00:08:31,740
 And it was also repeated by many early Christian authors, particularly by apologists, even by Tertullian.

57
00:08:31,900 --> 00:08:42,620
 Although in his writings, we also can see some ironic passages,

58
00:08:42,620 --> 00:08:51,180
 but he remains true to the basic concept of

59
00:08:52,460 --> 00:09:00,380
 explicit loyalty of the Christians to the emperor and to the secular power.

60
00:09:00,380 --> 00:09:08,700
 Now, the situation changed dramatically and also somehow rapidly

61
00:09:08,700 --> 00:09:16,860
 with the unexpected conversion of Constantine the Great at the beginning of the 4th century.

62
00:09:17,660 --> 00:09:28,220
 And it is important to quote the famous German church historian Hartmut Lepin who once wrote

63
00:09:28,220 --> 00:09:35,020
 that it was completely unimaginable even at the end of the 3rd century for the Christians

64
00:09:35,580 --> 00:09:48,700
 that emperor could be Christian because his functions were at the time so much connected to various forms of pagan worship.

65
00:09:48,700 --> 00:09:58,620
 So this change at the beginning of the 4th century was dramatic in more than one way.

66
00:09:59,260 --> 00:10:07,420
 And it also calls for the new definition of the relationship between

67
00:10:07,420 --> 00:10:12,140
 church and political authority, of course,

68
00:10:12,140 --> 00:10:19,660
 building on scriptural basis and on the basis of early apologists.

69
00:10:20,700 --> 00:10:31,820
 And there are two main starting points for the new definition of the relationship

70
00:10:31,820 --> 00:10:41,900
 between church and state, between bishops and emperor, between bishops and kings later on.

71
00:10:43,180 --> 00:10:53,820
 And this starting point in the west is a definition from the letter which the bishop of Rome,

72
00:10:53,820 --> 00:11:00,220
 Gelesius I, wrote to the Eastern Roman emperor, Anastasius I,

73
00:11:00,220 --> 00:11:10,300
 at the time of one of minor chisums in the history of the church at the end of the 5th century.

74
00:11:11,260 --> 00:11:23,900
 The other one is a similar definition written by the emperor Justinian I the Great somehow

75
00:11:23,900 --> 00:11:32,060
 some decades later at the beginning of the 6th century in the preface to his 6th novel.

76
00:11:33,900 --> 00:11:46,380
 And it is often assumed that this preface by the emperor Justinian forms the base

77
00:11:46,380 --> 00:11:56,220
 of the notion of the so-called symphony between church and state in Eastern Christian traditions,

78
00:11:56,860 --> 00:12:09,900
 which is supposed to be different to the somehow more conflict relationship between imperium and

79
00:12:09,900 --> 00:12:12,460
 sacerdotium in the west.

80
00:12:12,460 --> 00:12:20,300
 But if we read these ideological foundations or these ideal foundations

81
00:12:21,820 --> 00:12:32,300
 in Pope Gelesius and in the emperor Justinian, then we can say that all the basic ideas are the same.

82
00:12:32,300 --> 00:12:42,220
 They are two separate powers in the world according to both texts.

83
00:12:43,260 --> 00:12:51,740
 And one power is secular power represented by emperor or by political authority.

84
00:12:51,740 --> 00:12:58,540
 And the second power is spiritual power represented by priests and bishops.

85
00:12:59,740 --> 00:13:12,620
 And basically in both cases, these powers are equal also in Justinian and even more.

86
00:13:13,820 --> 00:13:28,860
 Both authors, Gelesius I and Justinian I emphasized that since holders of spiritual power, bishops and priests

87
00:13:28,860 --> 00:13:37,580
 perform their duties not only for themselves or for other people,

88
00:13:38,380 --> 00:13:47,740
 but also for holders of spiritual powers, they should enjoy particular respect.

89
00:13:47,740 --> 00:14:01,820
 And in this case, or from this origin, the highest worth of spiritual power could be deduced.

90
00:14:01,820 --> 00:14:11,340
 And this is not only limited to the Western view, to the ideas formulated by Pope Gelesius,

91
00:14:11,340 --> 00:14:23,100
 but the same notion is also present in this so-called Magna Carta of the idea of symphony by

92
00:14:23,980 --> 00:14:32,220
 and the emperor Justinian, the only difference is perhaps the person of both waters.

93
00:14:32,220 --> 00:14:41,580
 And it is, of course, significant that the definition of the proper relationship between

94
00:14:41,580 --> 00:14:50,460
 spiritual and secular power was defined by the Pope in the West,

95
00:14:50,460 --> 00:14:57,500
 by the bishop, by a bishop in the West, and by an emperor in the West, in the East.

96
00:14:57,500 --> 00:15:06,300
 And this by an emperor who was also an avid theologian, of course.

97
00:15:06,300 --> 00:15:16,140
 So we cannot assume that the foundations of the relationship between

98
00:15:18,380 --> 00:15:27,180
 church and political authorities is different in the East from that in the West.

99
00:15:27,180 --> 00:15:34,940
 What in fact was different was like Dr. Vedrish already

100
00:15:34,940 --> 00:15:44,620
 showed for another aspect of the building of these differences

101
00:15:46,380 --> 00:15:54,060
 between East and West was political development, which was in fact quite different

102
00:15:54,060 --> 00:16:03,340
 and was marked by a great and grave crisis of the secular authority in the West,

103
00:16:03,340 --> 00:16:10,780
 in the former Western part of the Roman Empire, and by the stability of the same secular power

104
00:16:10,780 --> 00:16:15,980
 and the secular authority in the Eastern part of the former Roman Empire.

105
00:16:15,980 --> 00:16:29,100
 Because even if the position of the emperor was held by a person who was personally weak,

106
00:16:29,100 --> 00:16:36,540
 like the famous Eastern Roman Empire, Theodosius II, in the first half of the fifth century,

107
00:16:37,740 --> 00:16:43,420
 the imperial authority in the East remained intact.

108
00:16:43,420 --> 00:16:52,300
 On the other hand, the case of Theodosius' relative, Valentinian III, in the West,

109
00:16:52,300 --> 00:17:05,900
 shows us that a weak emperor also weakened the idea of imperial authority itself.

110
00:17:06,700 --> 00:17:15,580
 Of course, particularly because of the fact that the objective circumstances of Valentinian's rule

111
00:17:15,580 --> 00:17:26,380
 were much more difficult in the West than the objective circumstances of Theodosius' rule in the East.

112
00:17:26,380 --> 00:17:38,940
 And then this crisis of secular power in the West only deepened from the end of the fifth century

113
00:17:38,940 --> 00:17:49,340
 till the revival of this secular power with the Franks in the early Middle Ages.

114
00:17:49,340 --> 00:18:01,900
 And that was an opportunity, of course, not an opportunity which was intended for the church

115
00:18:01,900 --> 00:18:12,860
 to establish herself as a much more independent institution in the West during the early Middle Ages.

116
00:18:13,740 --> 00:18:24,940
 And she retained her self-worn strength only after the revival of the secular power,

117
00:18:24,940 --> 00:18:28,620
 particularly since the beginning of the ninth century.

118
00:18:28,620 --> 00:18:41,740
 And that's why the relationship between church and secular authorities remained strained,

119
00:18:41,740 --> 00:18:46,780
 much more strained in the West than in the East,

120
00:18:46,780 --> 00:18:52,300
 where the imperial authority was never weakened.

121
00:18:53,020 --> 00:19:07,740
 Nevertheless, the basic idea of the need for cooperation between church and secular authorities remained vivid also in the West and was never abandoned.

122
00:19:08,540 --> 00:19:20,780
 So the notion of the so-called Reichskirche, as in the later Holy Roman Empire, was an ideal

123
00:19:20,780 --> 00:19:34,300
 which was never really abolished also in the West and was much more common than the periods of protracted conflicts.

124
00:19:34,300 --> 00:19:44,940
 Although particularly in the Catholic history, the emphasis is almost always on these cases of conflict,

125
00:19:44,940 --> 00:19:51,420
 like the famous conflict of investiture during the high Middle Ages.

126
00:19:52,380 --> 00:20:02,940
 And to conclude, there was also another development limited only to the West,

127
00:20:02,940 --> 00:20:15,580
 which probably changed the relationship between church and state for good in the West, but not in the East.

128
00:20:16,140 --> 00:20:27,420
 And this is the experience of wars of religion during the 16th and 17th centuries,

129
00:20:27,420 --> 00:20:40,300
 which put to the fore calls for separation between church and state,

130
00:20:40,940 --> 00:20:45,340
 and even between religion in society.

131
00:20:45,340 --> 00:20:53,580
 And this concept is something which is completely alien to the Eastern Christianity,

132
00:20:53,580 --> 00:21:04,620
 where this experience of wars of religion during the early modern age, of course, never existed.

133
00:21:05,340 --> 00:21:15,980
 And if the areas of Eastern Christianity ever accepted the idea of separation

134
00:21:15,980 --> 00:21:22,380
 between church and state, then it was, of course, imported from the West.

135
00:21:23,180 --> 00:21:34,140
 But it is clear, I think, from this presentation that basic foundations for the formation of relationship

136
00:21:34,140 --> 00:21:43,020
 between church and state in both parts of European Christianity

137
00:21:44,940 --> 00:22:01,100
 were basically the same and were founded on the same early experiences of the first church or early Christianity,

138
00:22:01,100 --> 00:22:05,340
 even before Constantine.

139
00:22:05,340 --> 00:22:08,780
 Thank you for your attention.

